{"builtWith":"0.15.15","comments":[{"LineComment":" ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━"},{"LineComment":"                          // hydrogen // schema // physical // optical // ior"},{"LineComment":" ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━"},{"LineComment":" | Complete Index of Refraction database for physically accurate rendering."},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | ## What is IOR?"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | The Index of Refraction (n) describes how much light slows down and bends"},{"LineComment":" | when entering a material. It's the ratio of light speed in vacuum to light"},{"LineComment":" | speed in the material: n = c / v"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | ## Physical Bounds"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | - **Minimum**: 1.0 (vacuum, by definition)"},{"LineComment":" | - **Maximum**: ~4.0 (germanium at infrared wavelengths)"},{"LineComment":" | - **Common range**: 1.0 - 2.5 for visible light applications"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | ## Why This Matters"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | At billion-agent scale, agents simulating materials need deterministic,"},{"LineComment":" | physically accurate values. When an agent creates \"diamond glass\" or"},{"LineComment":" | simulates \"underwater viewing\", they compose from these verified atoms."},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | For haptic/BMI applications, correct IOR affects:"},{"LineComment":" | - Visual perception of material density"},{"LineComment":" | - Sparkle and fire in gemstones"},{"LineComment":" | - Underwater distortion effects"},{"LineComment":" | - Lens and optical instrument simulation"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | ## Data Sources"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | Values from: CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, Gemological Institute"},{"LineComment":" | of America (GIA), peer-reviewed optical physics literature. All values"},{"LineComment":" | for sodium D-line (589nm) unless otherwise noted."},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | ## Module Structure"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | This is a leader module re-exporting from:"},{"LineComment":" | - `IOR.Core` - Type definition, operations, predicates, categories"},{"LineComment":" | - `IOR.Gases` - Vacuum, air, noble gases"},{"LineComment":" | - `IOR.Liquids` - Water, alcohols, organic solvents"},{"LineComment":" | - `IOR.Glass` - Common and optical glass types"},{"LineComment":" | - `IOR.Plastics` - Polymers and synthetic materials"},{"LineComment":" | - `IOR.Gemstones` - Precious, semi-precious, quartz, beryl, rare"},{"LineComment":" | - `IOR.Materials` - Crystals, metals, semiconductors, biological"},{"LineComment":" | - `IOR.Database` - Complete material lookup table"}],"decls":[],"exports":[],"foreign":[],"imports":[{"annotation":{"meta":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[107,12],"start":[75,1]}},"moduleName":["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Optical","IOR","Core"]},{"annotation":{"meta":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[246,16],"start":[244,1]}},"moduleName":["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Optical","IOR","Database"]},{"annotation":{"meta":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[120,13],"start":[109,1]}},"moduleName":["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Optical","IOR","Gases"]},{"annotation":{"meta":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[217,17],"start":[168,1]}},"moduleName":["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Optical","IOR","Gemstones"]},{"annotation":{"meta":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[153,13],"start":[138,1]}},"moduleName":["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Optical","IOR","Glass"]},{"annotation":{"meta":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[136,15],"start":[122,1]}},"moduleName":["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Optical","IOR","Liquids"]},{"annotation":{"meta":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[242,17],"start":[219,1]}},"moduleName":["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Optical","IOR","Materials"]},{"annotation":{"meta":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[166,16],"start":[155,1]}},"moduleName":["Hydrogen","Sc